Description.note: On May 18, 1926, Christian evangelist Aimee Semple McPherson disappeared from Venice Beach, California after going for a swim. She reappeared in Mexico five weeks later, stating she had escaped from kidnappers holding her for ransom there. Her disappearance, reappearance and subsequent court inquiries regarding the allegation that the kidnapping story was a hoax carried out to conceal a tryst with a lover precipitated a media frenzy that changed the course of McPherson's career.|~|Portrait photograph of Anna S. Wolf.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Department of Special Collections

Description.caption: Caption: Gen. Andres Pico owner of Rancho Los Coyotes in 1846 when California was conquered by the United States. The rancho was part of the ancient Los Nietos grant. Hazan - Dyson Collection.
Description.note: Andrés Pico  was a Californio who became a successful rancher, fought in the contested Battle of San Pascual during the Mexican–American War, and negotiated promises of post-war protections for Californios in the 1847 Treaty of Cahuenga. After California became one of the United States, Pico was elected to the state Assembly and Senate. He was appointed as the commanding brigadier general of the state militia during the U.S. Civil War.

The estate was opposite of that of President Roosevelt’s mother.|~|Father Divine points to a sign on the Crum Elbow estate. He is accompanied by a woman and a boy and a girl, perhaps his wife and children.|~|Father Divine (c. 1876–1965), also known as Reverend M. J. Divine, was an African-American spiritual leader[2] from about 1907, until his death. His full self-given name was Reverend Major Jealous Divine, and he was also known as "the Messenger" early in his life. He founded the International Peace Mission movement, formulated its doctrine, and oversaw its growth from a small and predominantly black congregation into a multiracial and international church. Due to his ideology, many consider him to be a cult leader.|~|Reported in: “Roosevelt foe laude Divine,” Los Angeles Times, 30 Jul. 1938: 2.

She reappeared in Mexico five weeks later, stating she had escaped from kidnappers holding her for ransom there. Her disappearance, reappearance and subsequent court inquiries regarding the allegation that the kidnapping story was a hoax carried out to conceal a tryst with a lover precipitated a media frenzy that changed the course of McPherson's career.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: John W. Wilson, manager of the Andrews Hotel, questioned during the McPherson trial, Los Angeles, 1926

Description.note: Press release text: East west non stop record set. Establishing an east-to-west transcontinental nonstop flight record of 24 hours and 52 minutes, the monoplane Yankee Doodle landed at Mines Field, Los Angeles, today. The previous record of 26 hours and 50 minutes set by Lts. John A. MacReady and Oakley Kelly in 1923 was lowered by nearly two hours in the flight. The fliers, Harry Tucker, millionaire sportsman and Capt. C. B. D. Collyer of 'round-the-world' fame, landed a little more that an hour after the time estimated for the journey. The monoplane used in this flight was also used by Art Goebel in his attempted non-stop flight during the National Aeronautical Show held in Los Angeles recently...

Name.subject: McPherson, Aimee Semple, $d 1890-1944|~|Wallace, Evelyn
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Department of Special Collections
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Wallace, Evelyn. McPherson case.
Description.note: On May 18, 1926, Christian evangelist Aimee Semple McPherson disappeared from Venice Beach, California after going for a swim. She reappeared in Mexico five weeks later, stating she had escaped from kidnappers holding her for ransom there. Her disappearance, reappearance and subsequent court inquiries regarding the allegation that the kidnapping story was a hoax carried out to conceal a tryst with a lover precipitated a media frenzy that changed the course of McPherson's career.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: Evelyn Wallace, related to the McPherson trial, Los Angeles, 1926

Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: McCoy, Kid boxer - murder 1924|~|Text from newspaper caption: They Knew the Kid When-- Harry Pollock was twenty years McCoy's manager and Tom Kennedy was his sparring partner, and they sat together yesterday and watched what may be his last fight in his trial for the murder of Teresa Mors. Description.note: From left to right, Harry Pollock (Kid McCoy's former manager) and Tom Kennedy (Kid McCoy's sparring partner) sit side-by-side in the courtroom's gallery during McCoy's trial. Description.caption: Handwritten text from negative sleeve: McCoy, Kid boxer - murder 1924|~|Text from newspaper caption: [Photo by George R. Watson. Times staff photographer] The Toughest Fight! McCoy, on the witness stand demonstrates to the jury, the manner in which Mrs. Mors held the butcher knife when affirms she tried to stab herself. On McCoy's left is his attorney, H. L. Giesler. Judge Crail is on the bench. [Los Angeles Times, 20 Dec. 1924: A1]
Description.note: This photograph appears with the article, "Former Ring Idol Enacts Death Scene on Witness Stand: DEFENSE CLOSES AS KID REVEALS FAMILY TAINT Ex-Pugilist Enacts His Version of Mrs. Mors's Death Before Jury; Arguments on Monday," Los Angeles Times, 20 Dec. 1924: A1|~|At center, Kid McCoy (nee Norman Selby) sits on the witness stand in his own defense during his murder trial. With both hands, he holds a knife towards the center of his chest, reenacting Mrs. Teresa Mors' alleged attempt to stab herself. He glances to his attorney, Jerry Giesler, who stands to the left of McCoy. At right, Judge Crail sits at the judge's bench and looks towards McCoy. The floor plan of an apartment stands behind Giesler at left. Kid McCoy was on trial for the murder of Teresa Mors.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: Kid McCoy, defendant, testifies during his murder trial, Los Angeles, 1924

"West Cadron" [stamped:] JAN 14 1936|~|Text from newspaper caption: Caught in a ninety-mile-an-hour hurricane off the mouth of the Columbia River, the Iowa of the States Steamship Line was smashed to pieces yesterday. Capt. Elgar L. Yates, making his first voyage on the Iowa, and his entire crew of thirty-three men were lost. The gale was so terrific that a Coast Guard cutter which set out in an effort to effect rescue of the crew was unable to approach the vessel. Other ships also were reported in distress in the same vicinity during the most violent storm there in years. [Los Angeles Times, 13 Jan. 1936: 2]
Description.note: This photograph appears with the titled, "States Line Freighter Iowa Wrecked With Loss of Its Entire Crew," Los Angeles Times, 13 Jan. 1936: 2|~|The SS West Cadron (later SS Iowa) sits moored in an unknown port at center. It is viewed from its starboard side with the stern at left and the bow at right. On the bow, markings read, "WEST CA[...]." It was later renamed the SS Iowa in 1928 and eventually sank near the Columbia River in 1936.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: SS West Cadron in port, circa 1920-1928

Description.caption: Text from newspaper caption: Highest relief officials met here yesterday to discuss the local relief crisis. Here they are, left to right: Robert H. Hinckley of Salt Lake City, Federal relief administrator for the Western States; Col. Lawrence Westbrook of Washington, D. C., assistant national relief administrator; Frank Y. McLaughlin of San Francisco, Federal and State relief administrator in California; Col. Donald H. Connolly, Federal Works Progress Administrator in Los Angeles county.|~|Text from negative sleeve: 2420 - Robert Hinckley Lawrence Westbrook Frank Y. Mc Laughlin Col. Donald H. Connolly 12/20/35|~|Text from insert in negative sleeve: 12/18/35. L-R Robert H. Hinckley, Salt Lake City, Regional director for F.E.R.A. [Federal Emergency Relief Administration] and W.P.A. [Works Progress Administration]; Col. Lawrence Westbrook, Washington, D.C., assistant national relief administrator; Frank Y. McLaughlin, San Francisco, California state administrator for F.E.R.A., S.E.R.A. [State Emergency Relief Administration] and W.P.A.; Col. Donald H. Connolly, W.P.A. director in Los Angeles County.
Description.note: The relief officials are unsure whether the Federal Relief program will work to improve conditions in California during the Great Depression, but are optimistic and express the ability to revamp it if it doesn't work.|~|The four men sit on sofas surrounding a large open book.|~|Photograph appears with the article, "Aid Program Under Test," Los Angeles Times, 19 Dec 1935: A1.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: State and Federal Relief officials confer in Los Angeles, 1935

New Depot. - "Drawing" [stamped:] Jul 17 1935|~|Text accompanying photograph in article: This sketch illustrates the general character of the new union passenger station east of the Plaza and the $2,600,000 working postoffice, as suggested by government architects. The station, surmounted by a tower, is on the right. A public concourse with an arcade surrounding a garden separate the station and the postoffice.
Description.note: The sketch was sent by Admiral C. J. Peoples, director of the procurement division, Treasury Department to Mayor Frank Shaw. Three paper clips are on the top edge.|~|This photograph appears in "Preliminary Government Drawing of New Union Station and Working Postoffice" and is related to "New Postoffice Sketch Sent From Washington," Los Angeles Times, 13 Jul 1935: A1.

Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: 1205. Jno Ed Healey; C P Stevens; Det Lt. ^Miles Ledbetter; Capt Bert Wallis [two lines drawn under Capt Bert Wallis] [upside down:] Stevens- C. P.; Ledbetter- Dt. Lt. - Wallis-- Capt Bert|~|Handwritten on negative: C. P. Stevens; Dt. Lt. Ledbetter; Capt Bert Wallis
Description.note: Captain Bert Wallis (left), Detective Lieutenant Miles H. Ledbetter (center), and Charles P. Stevens sit in front of a desk. The desk has wire inboxes with stacks of paper in them. A check spindle with a sheet of paper impaled on it is also on the desk. Wallis and Ledbetter wear three piece suits. Stevens wears a suit jacket, but no tie, and his shirt top button is undone. He is pointing at Wallis with his right hand. A window is behind them, and on the wall is a photograph with fifteen men posing for a picture.|~|John Edward Healey (John E. Healey) is not in this negative. He appears with Ledbetter and Wallis in negative 7527.|~|C. P. Stevens was an ex-Los Angeles policeman and a wanted fugitive for the murder of Mike Mucich in 1921. He was recaptured in Sacramento on April 11, 1935. He was found guilty and sentenced to death, but his sentence was later commuted to a life sentence by Governor Merriam. He was paroled in 1949.|~|Related to "Old Murder Hunt Closes: Ex-Officer Held as Suspect," Los Angeles Times, 12 Apr 1935: 11 and "Gang 'Ride' Case Sped," Los Angeles Times, 16 Apr 1935: A5.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: Captain Bert Wallis (left), Detective Lieutenant Miles Ledbetter (center), and C. P. Stevens, recaptured fugitive, Los Angeles, 1935

Whiteley (left) and Gladys Hamilton stand before a diagram of Busby Berkeley's automobile accident. The diagram has three cars drawn on it as rectangles and distances marked out. Hamilton is pointing at the diagram with her right hand. She is wearing a hat and plaid coat with large buttons over a sweater and collared shirt. Whiteley is wearing a three piece suit.|~|Gladys Belle Hamilton and John Carl Whitely were married by the 1940 census. She became Gladys B. Whiteley.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: Gladys Hamiliton and John Carl Whiteley, witnesses at Busby Berkeley's trial, Los Angeles, 1936

Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Lorraine, David G.
Description.note: Living in Texas in the 1920s and financed by $18,000 from his first wife, Rose, David G. Lorraine invented and patented oil-field machinery. In 1925, David G. Lorraine offered Rose $10,000 for her share of the corporation, claiming he was about to go bankrupt. He then divorced her, moved to California, remarried, and his company prospered, making him wealthy. Rose initiated a law suit to gain her rightful share of the wealth, claiming Lorraine had deliberately deceived her. She won her law suit.

Description.caption: Handwritten on negative sleeve: 1047. Dorothy Oaks With Rose & Cabbage which were sent to Judge White of Superior Court during the Guttman-Sewell Case [Guttman underlined in red pencil]  7/10/35 [stamped:] Aug 8 1935|~|Text on gift cards: left: Sorry just-- Cabbage […] not send […] Giggolo [sic]; Mr. Chas R. Morfoot, Dept 13, 18th Floor, City Hall. right: Darling's Shop. Yes, Yes, Yes. Hon. Judge White, Dept. 13, 18th Floor, City Hall|~|Handwritten on negative: Dorothy Oaks 7/10/35
Description.note: Henry A. Guttman, posing as a financial expert/promoter, was lent over $40,000 in stock by Blanche Sewell. He never returned it and was charged with 8 counts of grand theft. He was found guilty of 2 counts, not guilty on 3 counts, and the jury deadlocked on the other 3 counts. He was sentenced for 1-10 years, but mercy was granted and he was instead put on 10 years probation after serving 9 months at a county road camp. Judge White presided over this case, and Charles Morfoot was Guttman's attorney.|~|Dorothy Oaks stands behind a table, holding gifts for Judge Thomas P. White and defense attorney Charles R. Morfoot. In her left hand, she holds up a rose lying in tissue paper in a box. By her right hand on the table, is a gift wrapped circular bundle. Judge White is being gifted a rose, while Morfoot is being gifted a cabbage.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: Dorothy Oaks holds gifts for Judge Thomas P. White and Charles R. Morfoot who were working the Guttman-Sewell case, Los Angeles, 1935

Vol. I. Los Angeles, Cal. July [illegible] L.A. PISTOL TEAM VICTORS [illegible] L. A. P. D. PISTOL TEAM [illegible] AGAIN [rest illegible].|~|Handwritten on negative: L2R H. B. Rozzen + J. F. Description.note: H. B. Rozzen was a police stenographer. Joseph F. Fueger was a teletype operator (who was later arrested for robbing stores at knifepoint). Lena Greenstein may also have been a police stenographer.|~|Three police workers in charge of the police bulletin, "The Communicator," at the mimeograph machine. H. B. Rozzen (left, seated), has a pencil in his right hand and posing with a candlestick phone, holding the earpiece up to his ear with his left. J. F. Fueger (center) stands at the mimeograph machine, holding the crank with his left hand and removing a sheet of paper from the machine with his right. The men are looking at each other, smiling. Lena Greenstein stands reading a finished bulletin, smiling. The men wear three piece suits and Greenstein wears a sweater dress.

Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: J. W. Mosher & Chas. W. Ostrom|~|Handwritten on negative sleeve: Mosher, Wm J. appointed in 1929; Mayor's investigating secretary; former probation officer in San Diego County, L.A., Prohibition officer & LA County secret service (undercover Sheriff's liquor squad).|~|Text on sign in background: SHERIFF'S BARBEQUE; CALIFORNIA ZOOLOGICAL GARDENS [Form]erly Luna Park Zoo; JULY 17, 1932|~|Text on calendar on wall: Where Permanence is Assured; INGLEWOOD PARK CEMETERY Largest in California MAUSOLEUM = COLUMBARIUM = CREMATORIUM 1932 JULY 1932
Description.note: Wells J. Mosher (left) and Charles W. Ostrom stand next to each other in a hallway. To the right of Ostrom is a wall calendar and a locked door. Behind them are a table and a radiator. On the wall behind them are several framed portraits, a sticker (?) portrait, and a sign for a barbecue. Mosher wears a suit, jacket unbuttoned, and had his hands crossed in front of him, holding a light-colored hat. A pencil and a pair of glasses is in his jacket pocket. Ostrom wears a tweed suit, jacket also unbuttoned, and has his hands clasped behind his back.|~|A different photograph taken on the same day as this one appears in "Mayor's Ex-Aide Surrenders to Court," and is related to "Grand Jurors Indict Mosher," Los Angeles Times, 08 Jul 1932: A1|~|Wells J. Mosher was indicted by a grand jury, charging him with conspiracy to frame Police Commissioner Thomas Walkup. Charles W. Ostrom was his lawyer. W. J. Mosher was the confidential secretary to Mayor John C. Porter.|~|Names on negative sleeve and negative do not match each other, nor the actual name. Wm. J. Mosher and J. W. Mosher should be Wells J. Mosher, or W. J. Mosher.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.|~|Access to this collection is generously supported by Haynes Foundation funds.
Title: Wells J. Mosher, ex-confidential secretary to Mayor Porter, and his lawyer, Charles Ostrom, Los Angeles, 1932

Leach wearing a three piece double breasted suit.|~|Martin A. Leach was the president of the Leach Biltwell Motor Car Company and the head of the Pacific Southwest Loan and Mortgage Corporation and the National Loan Company. He was shot in his office by Louis Richert, one of his investors. He was previously arrested for fraud but the charges were dismissed, but then was later again arrested for fraud for selling worthless mortgage notes. Description.note: Left to right: Ralph Wallace, William Mosley Jones and Ralph Welsh seated at the bench during a hearing in the California State Building in Los Angeles.|~|Ralph Welsh was an assemblyman in Los Angeles, and chairman of the Oil Industries Committee.|~|William Mosley Jones of Montebello was the Speaker of the California State Assembly.|~|Justice Gavin W. Craig was an associate justice of Division Two of the Second District of the State Courts of Appeal. His right to hold that position was challenged, on the basis of charges of attempted obstruction of justice in the Italo Petroleum Company case. There was a State Assembly hearing in the California State Building in which the Los Angeles Bar Association … demanded that the Assembly and Senate remove the justice [Gavin W. Craig.] by concurrent resolution. William Mosley Jones of Montebello; Ralph Wallace of San Diego, and Ralph L. Welsh of Los Angeles, with Jones acting as chairman, conducted the Assembly hearing, took statements of the Los Angeles Bar Association representatives and of other interested parties.|~|Reported in: “Webb files suit to oust Gavin Craig: Bar also makes removal plea,” Los Angeles Times, 26 May 1935: 1.|~|Ralph Wallace was a California Assemblyman of San Diego.

Description.note: Mr. Casad is said to have discovered an apple tree growing on the property of H.E. Ellery that grows massive fruit weighing over two pounds and measuring eighteen inches around the waist. He considers himself to be a melon grower and experimenter.|~|Story related to photograph appears with the article, "Big Apples Produced at Oceanside," Los Angeles Times, 08 Nov 1925: J6.|~|The gourd that Mr. Casad is holding has the following carved onto it in English: “Read the Los Angeles Times for news and advertising.  Read ‘Unemployment and It’s Solution’ By Roland C. Castro for Ideas!”|~|Roland holds a large vegetable that looks like a squash which has carved on it "READ THE LOS ANGELES TIMES FOR NEWS AND ADVERTISING, READ "UNEMPLOYMENT AND ITS SOLUTION" BY ROLAND C CASAD FOR IDEAS!"

Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: Mc Pherson, Aimee Semple, Telegrams Notes
Description.note: n 1926 evangelist Aimee Semple McPherson disappeared from Venice Beach in California  for 5 weeks. Thought to have drowned, she emerged in Mexico, claiming to have been kidnapped. A grand jury investigation indicated that she had actually been staying with a former employee, Kenneth Ormiston. The case against McPherson was finally dismissed.|~|From the note: "San Francisco, May 18th, Temple Angelus, Los Angeles--We have with us your beloved Aimee McPherson and will free her on payment of 500,000.00 in currency to be paid, at once in this manner. She has injured us and must pay in money or blood,--Select your man and have him take a seat in the Palace Hotel Lobby..."
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.
Title: Aimee McPherson's alleged ransom note, 1926
